metadata.name: Type-o-Graphic #360
metadata.description:
Type-o-Graphic embraces the ethos of David Carson's groundbreaking graphic design work. It explores the intersections of typography, design, art and chance, harnessing the power of randomness to create a series of posters that are a frenetic celebration of typographic chaos.

This collection is intended to be customized and printed. Your initial thumbnail output is only the beginning ‚Äî several parameters are changeable to find a combination and format to your liking. Please use the keys below to explore the thousands of possible variations within each piece.

Features:
B - Toggle border
N - Change border colour
K - Change background colour (if visible)
T - Toggle top finish (if applicable)
Up/Down - Change colour palette (43)
Left/Right - Change blend modes (20)
L - Change to Landscape
P - Change to Portrait
S - Save image

0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 - Change resolution of image
0 - 600 x 900 - (low-res)
1 - 1200 x 1800 - 4x6" @ 300dpi - (default)
2 - 2400 x 3600 - 8x12" @ 300dpi
3 - 3600 x 5400 ‚Äì 12x18" @ 300dpi
4 - 4800 x 7200 - 16x24" @ 300dpi
5 - 7200 x 10800 - 24x36" @ 300dpi

See accompanying article for more info:
https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/type-o-graphic

Created with p5js by fauxjebus in 2023
Follow me on twitter or instagram @fauxjebus

metadata.name: ombromanie #135
metadata.description:
‚ÄúHow hands can create the vision that germinates in my mind? And what if the vision directly sprouts from the hands instead of the mind‚Äù, the artist asks.
‚ÄúIs the vision thrown through the shadow of the hands, or is the shadow hands the vision itself?‚Äù, the magician responds.
As an attempt to add a line to this whimsical dialogue, I dropped shadows to cast visions. To my great surprise, the artist and the magician blent into each other‚Ä¶

- - -

‚ÄúOmbromanie‚Äù refers to the art of creating images made by hand shadows. The word and the art (also called ‚Äúshadowgraphy‚Äù) was popularized by french magician F√©licien Trewey in the XIXth century. Sure the shadow art is not so popular nowadays, but it still shares with generative art part of the same mystery and magic. The code projects shapes and colors on a screen to create images; the hands project a shadow on a curtain to create figures.

‚ÄúOmbromanie‚Äù was conceived as a curtain where articulated hands (or better, shadow of hands) throw a firework of shapes, creating a wide range of random compositions. I heard the magician words and I did implement five features for this magical trick:
- the curtain can be entire or hemmed,
- the image oriented the right way up or upside-down,
- one or two hands can be used for the invocation,
- the phatasmagoria reveals itself as syzygy or chaos,
- and climax is reached through twelve ways.
Hands are always present, but in extremely rare cases they could vanish behind the curtain‚Ä¶   

- - - 

This project uses twelve custom color palettes ‚Äì the climaxes.
Ten are inspired after works or body of works by well known generative artists. A kind of tribute for the constant inspiration and creativity of the magicians-artists.
- ‚ÄúHollow‚Äù by @jMarkusiewicz
- ‚ÄúGarden, Monoliths‚Äù by @zancan
- ‚ÄúUninhabitable‚Äù by @pointline_
- ‚ÄúMimizu‚Äù by @qubibien
- ‚Äúaether:Astral Loom‚Äù by @lisaorthstudio
- ‚Äúgestalt‚Äù by @Yazid
- ‚ÄúPerpendicular Inhabitation‚Äù (night) by @StudioYorktown
- ‚ÄúAnaverse‚Äù by @anaglyph_ic
- ‚ÄúTake wing‚Äù by @mwiederrecht
- ‚Äúcontrapuntos‚Äù by @msoriaro
The eleventh palette is named ‚Äúfakewhale‚Äù(@fakewhale_xyz), who, months ago, encouraged me to learn and try code to create generative works. Special thanks to them for the support and dialogue.
The twelfth palette refers to my first long form generative project called ‚Äùth√©ba√Øde‚Äù.

- - -

A small word about the ‚Äúphatasmagoria‚Äù part, which tells about the invisible thread that sews my artistic approach. This part is a modified and extended code I used to create a set of six pieces titled ‚ÄúSketches for unreliable structure‚Äù (Objkt, December 2022). And those were already an echo from a selection of digital (but not coded) works from ‚ÄúThe Queue Structure‚Äù project (Objkt, since May 2022). Finally, The Queue Structure itself was a visual laboratory nourished by my previous practice of abstraction in the tangible world (drawing, collage, monotype, engraving). 

- - -

Press ‚Äús‚Äù in live mode to save the work as a PNG (default 2000 √ó 2000 px).
Add to the URL ‚Äù&size=n‚Äù (number from 3 to 10) to render an image at higher resolution (from 3000 px to 10000 px). It may last for high numbers.
We recommend the use of Chrome browser in order to render properly the texture.

Made with p5js | 2023
Png |¬†2000 √ó 2000 px | 72 ppi

www.antoniowerli.net

metadata.name: caravans #141
metadata.description:
This piece is inspired by Paul Klee's 'Zwei Kamele und ein Esel' (Two camels and a donkey), abacuses and excessive shopping sprees.

An anonymous caravan makes its way through abstract deserts, carrying their semi-brutalist cargo towards an unknown destination.

All primary proceeds go to the Processing foundation.

Happy birthday fxhash!

Written in JavaScript, rendering to Canvas.

metadata.name: Lanes of Travel #103
metadata.description:
How do you get from place to place?

Inspired by metro subway maps and electrical circuit boards, Lines of Travel explores imaginary routes that may have been! 

Occasionally a seismic shift might happen, resulting in routes that deviate across layers creating distortions. 

This generative art is designed to exist in the real world as a 14 layer sculpture which is cut from 4-ply museum board. It is optimally sized for 16x20in but also looks great as an 8x10 or 24x30. Perhaps even engraved into an anodized metal card. 

I‚Äôll pick a selection of my favorite outputs to turn into a curated physical collection that will be exhibited and available for purchase by the general public. 

Holders of the curated editions tokens will receive the first 16x20in numbered and signed physical edition which can be claimed after it‚Äôs gallery showing is finished. 

Physical editions can be commissioned by the token owner at https://alleditions.art 

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

Click and drag to change the light source. 
Tap s to export SVG
Tap p to export PNG
Tap e to explode the layers

metadata.name: Brinco #111
metadata.description:
As slinkies rise and sway through flurries of confetti, sometimes this play is focused and orderly. At other times, they crowd together riotously, conspiring to sneak off the sides altogether.

"Brinco" (Portuguese for "I play") is about celebrating finding joy in my creative pursuits again; about not overthinking it and simply following what makes me happy.

Creative joy can be capricious, leaving us when we need it the most. We hope we can relate to our artistic practice in a positive way, tapping into what feels like a bottomless source of energy and excitement. But sometimes when life becomes overwhelming, what gave you energy before now feels hollow and rote‚Äîjust one more thing sapping at you, and an emptiness where creative passion once resided.

For over a year, I've been sitting in this shadow. Until one day, I sat down and started tinkering‚Ä¶ and for the first time in such a long time, I started to feel the spark.

I hope that viewers and collectors feel that same spark of joy and playfulness when seeing these pieces that I've felt creating them.

Press "s"/"S" to save a PNG at the current size and press "h"/"H" to save a high resolution version.

metadata.name: inlim:in #241
metadata.description:
"inlim:in" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at PARIS+ par Art Basel

Atemporal iridescent fragments of the in between. The series is inspired by the many liminal spaces and unseen influences that permeate the visible universe and its participants. Created with GLSL, every piece of the series is generated using the space around the visible object to cast its shape. The series creates a gentle and colorful expanse through which viewers might contemplate what it is to exist at an infinite threshold.

metadata.name: Emotions #89
metadata.description:
This is a collection inspired by the intense emotions I experienced while creating it.
It‚Äôs a combination of joy, anxiety, anger & hope all mixed on the canvas and visualized using p5js. I‚Äôm almost sure that if you look at these pieces you will find some of your own emotions in it.
From a technical standpoint, it is an exploration of flow fields and different color blending techniques.

Controls (in live view):

- press 'd' to generate 3000x4000 image
- press 's' to save the PNG image of the current view

metadata.name: PARIS #162
metadata.description:
Paris is a generative and animated piece creating shapes based on trails. 
The size, position and motion frequency of each circles are generated for each token, along with the color theme. 

Each reloading creates a different movement, as the algorithm underlying the piece is partially based on a noise.
At the end, the animation stop and the visual is created.

Created by Quentin Hocd√©, in La-Roche-Neuville (France).

metadata.name: 03. world of boxland #63
metadata.description:
Boxland is made of boxes, of 262.144 boxes to be more precise. These boxes are rearranged whenever an observer moves around generating an infinite landscape.

Landscape is generated using fbm noise at different frequencies so the algorithm can define areas where there is water, shores that are in constant movement and the mountains that can get high up to the sky. 

Users can control the camera point of view, although it is always performing a fly through the never ending world.


Features tied to the hash : 
- General color palette
- Landscape seed
- Water amount (you can get archipelagos or vast landscapes)
- Camera position

metadata.name: bad burn #24
metadata.description:
Lightning strikes the screen and pixels burn, decay, fall off the edge. I encourage you to read the source code, change some values around, and find a remix that scratches your itch. Written and debugged in Pico-8.

creator: Alex Scott
source: https://pastebin.com/P5rLHVzy
date: 2021-11-22 11:00pm
twitter: @alexthescott
website: alexthescott.space
platform: Pico-8, Lua

Inspired by the 1990 film and narration by Rudy Rucker. Without this, I would have not learned of the Vote rule!

metadata.name: Misty Mountains #2
metadata.description:
A mountain range scribbled on a scrap piece of paper.

The smudging drenches the mountains further back into a thick fog while creating a pixelated background.


Please note that there is no smudging in the preview as it requires a GPU, so the previews will look different.


Features:
Full/Wading/Waxing Moon
6 Color palettes including monochrome
Black (20% chance) or White  sheet of paper

There are further variables that will affect the style in which the mountains and fog are drawn which are dependent on the hash. The outcomes can vary quite a bit. Check the variations function to see the possible results.

Controls:
S - Save 2000x2000 image
Space - Pause/Unpause animation
Up/Down-Arrows - Increase/Decrease speed


Created on 2D Canvas in Vanilla Js.

metadata.name: She speaks in accents #69
metadata.description:
"There is no language that speaks so powerfully to the mind as that of Nature. It is intelligible both to the young and to the old, to the ignorant and to the learned, to the lisping infant as well as to the hoary age, to the untutored savage of the forest as well as to the most favored votary of science." Language of Flowers, 1834

The artwork takes the form of generative botanical compositions and is based on the Victorian Language of Flowers. At the times natural expressions of feelings were frowned upon and highly discouraged, flowers became a communicational tool conveying one's delicate feelings to another, yet in a socially acceptable manner. For successful translation, the interlocutors resorted to publications that collected meanings for each plant and its presentation in a particular context. The piece is based on a range of dictionaries and generates compositions with messages nature carries this season. The materials were picked and scanned by the author. The generative code was written by @neelts

metadata.name: Giza #125
metadata.description:
Tried to catch a poetic atmosphere working on this generative representation of the pyramids of Giza.
Built by thousands of humans during tens of years thousands years ago they're now generated in seconds with millions of dots by a javascript algorithm.
That's were knowledge has led us !

Features
 - Time: Day (probability 1/2) / Night (probability 1/2)
 - Mode: Dark (probability 5/6) / Light (probability 1/6)
 - Number of pyramids
 - Background dunes
 - Global ligthness
 - Sun/Moon shine
 - generative color palette

Only Javascript / No library used

metadata.name: MEGASTRUCTURES #74
metadata.description:
MEGASTRUCTURES is a fully generative artwork. It renders a variety of space-age scenes, decaying megastructures left floating in space for centuries. 

It features:

- 4 Scenes
- 5 Star Colors
- 2 Star Positions
- 2 Star Sizes
- 3 levels of megastructure destruction / decay
- Special RAINBOW Variants


Megastructures can be plotted with the removal of occlusions using either illustrator or the occult vpype plugin. 

To save the piece as an SVG press any key. Note outputs may take some time depending on how powerful your device is.

metadata.name: random(four) #44
metadata.description:
Building on four‚Äôs participation in the Blind Gallery Bear Market Edition, random(four) replaces the use of tezos price data with randomized inputs.  Other qualities/design aspects have been revised slightly to allow for a more diverse set of outputs. 

Made with p5js, triangles, and no tezos price data.

Press 1-9 to render higher quality outputs; rendering time will vary.
